<!-- END APPRAISAL FORM -->
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      I work the western corridor and understand how Chapel Hill sits in the buyer decision. The suburb draws a specific and committed buyer profile: families who have done their research on Kenmore State High School and identified the catchment as a genuine priority, buyers upgrading from the density of Toowong or Indooroopilly who want a proper backyard without leaving the inner-western orbit, and long-term Brisbane residents who know exactly which streets deliver the best combination of elevation, canopy and privacy. These buyers are patient, well-researched and move with conviction when the right property appears.
    </p>
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      Moggill Road and the Western Freeway provide the primary arterial connections eastward to the CBD and westward toward Kenmore. Bus services along Moggill Road connect directly to the city, and off-peak the drive from Chapel Hill to the CBD takes approximately 20 to 25 minutes. The housing stock is predominantly post-war and mid-century detached homes on generous blocks, with a growing number of well-executed renovations and contemporary rebuilds that have updated the suburb's quality base without changing its fundamental character. The elevation and tree canopy are what buyers pay for, and they are the features that make Chapel Hill genuinely difficult to replicate elsewhere in the western corridor.
    </p>
    <div style="display:flex; gap:1.5rem; flex-wrap:wrap;">
      <div style="flex:1; min-width:200px; background:#fff; padding:1.75rem; border-left:3px solid #b98229; border-radius:16px;">
        <p style="font-family:var(--font-serif); font-size:1.1rem; font-weight:400; color:#191817; margin-bottom:0.4rem;">Chapel Hill Specialist</p>
